French Agency Seeks Safeguards on Sheep Intestines to Reduce BSE Risk
-----------------------------------------------
PARIS: France's food safety agency AFSSA on Wednesday renewed its call to
toughen safeguards on sheep and goat products due to the theoretical risk
of these animals acquiring bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE) and
passing it to humans.
In a 50-page report on the risks of BSE, the agency asked the government to
add intestines--used for sausages--to the list of specified risk material
(SRM) that must be removed from the food chain. "The current system [in
France excludes from human consumption most of the most infectious tissues
in small ruminants and should, by that logic, include the intestines of
small ruminants whatever their age," AFSSA said.
Current rules against the sheep disease scrapie require the removal of
certain SRM--spleen, tonsils, spinal cord, and most of the head--depending
on the animal's age, because of fears they could transmit BSE.
AFSSA first proposed extending the list of SRMs for sheep and goats to
intestines more than a year ago, but its calls raised controversy in France
and abroad. French President Jacques Chirac accused the agency of "inciting
panic."
There is no scientific evidence of the transmission of BSE to sheep and
goats, and consequently to humans, but the hypothesis cannot be ruled out,
AFSSA said. The agency therefore urged the government to launch a
nationwide system to enable all small ruminants to be traced and identified
and to systematically test dead animals for transmissible spongiform
encephalopathies (TSEs). It also suggested a genetic improvement plan that
would aim to increase resistance to TSEs among sheep.
The agency said that all the measures should be extended to all sheep and
goats imported into France as imports exceed domestic production.
